1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,405
As large language models grow,

2
00:00:02,405 --> 00:00:05,773
we face a fundamental physics crisis: a

3
00:00:05,773 --> 00:00:08,659
direct trade-off between capability and computation.

4
00:00:08,659 --> 00:00:12,027
Training and running a trillion-parameter dense model

5
00:00:12,027 --> 00:00:17,319
requires unfathomable compute power, threatening to melt silicon and bankrupt enterprises.

6
00:00:17,319 --> 00:00:20,687
But what if we could scale a

7
00:00:20,687 --> 00:00:24,055
model's knowledge capacity to hundreds of billions

8
00:00:24,055 --> 00:00:27,904
of parameters while keeping its computational footprint constant?

9
00:00:27,904 --> 00:00:33,196
This is the core genius of Mixture of Experts, or MoE.

10
00:00:33,196 --> 00:00:36,563
Today, we will explore MoE routing: the

11
00:00:36,563 --> 00:00:41,856
high-performance dispatching algorithm that powers modern models like Mixtral and DeepSeek.

12
00:00:41,856 --> 00:00:44,725
In a traditional dense neural network,

13
00:00:44,725 --> 00:00:48,073
every single token must pass through every

14
00:00:48,073 --> 00:00:50,943
single weight parameter in the model.

15
00:00:50,943 --> 00:00:54,291
If a model has eighty billion parameters,

16
00:00:54,291 --> 00:00:58,595
then every word generated requires eighty billion active FLOPs.

17
00:00:58,596 --> 00:01:01,465
This is the dense scaling trap.

18
00:01:01,465 --> 00:01:04,813
Expanding model capability requires increasing active parameters,

19
00:01:04,813 --> 00:01:09,596
which directly raises compute latency, hardware costs, and energy requirements.

20
00:01:09,596 --> 00:01:11,987
To break this linear relationship,

21
00:01:11,987 --> 00:01:16,292
we must transition from dense compute to sparse compute,

22
00:01:16,292 --> 00:01:19,640
activating only the precise neural pathways we

23
00:01:19,640 --> 00:01:22,032
need for each specific token.

24
00:01:22,032 --> 00:01:25,238
A Sparse Mixture of Experts network replaces

25
00:01:25,238 --> 00:01:28,444
the standard dense Feed-Forward layer with a

26
00:01:28,444 --> 00:01:32,108
set of parallel subnetworks called "Experts." For instance,

27
00:01:32,108 --> 00:01:34,398
a model might have eight,

28
00:01:34,398 --> 00:01:38,062
sixteen, or even two hundred and fifty-six experts.

29
00:01:38,062 --> 00:01:42,642
Crucially, each individual expert is a standard, compact neural network.

30
00:01:42,642 --> 00:01:45,849
When a token enters the MoE layer,

31
00:01:45,849 --> 00:01:48,139
it doesn't visit all experts.

32
00:01:48,139 --> 00:01:51,345
Instead, it is dynamically routed to a

33
00:01:51,345 --> 00:01:55,925
tiny fraction of them—typically just the top-one or top-two experts.

34
00:01:55,925 --> 00:01:59,131
By doing this, we keep the total

35
00:01:59,131 --> 00:02:01,879
active parameters per token extremely low,

36
00:02:01,879 --> 00:02:05,544
even as the total model capacity grows massive.

37
00:02:05,544 --> 00:02:08,591
At the heart of this sparse architecture

38
00:02:08,591 --> 00:02:11,638
is the gating network, or the Router.

39
00:02:11,638 --> 00:02:13,815
The Router is a simple,

40
00:02:13,815 --> 00:02:16,862
lightweight linear layer that takes a token's

41
00:02:16,862 --> 00:02:19,910
hidden representation and decides which experts are

42
00:02:19,910 --> 00:02:22,086
best equipped to process it.

43
00:02:22,086 --> 00:02:25,134
It computes a numerical routing score for

44
00:02:25,134 --> 00:02:28,181
each expert by performing a matrix multiplication

45
00:02:28,181 --> 00:02:32,535
between the token's representation and a learned routing weight matrix.

46
00:02:32,535 --> 00:02:35,582
This produces a vector of raw logits—one

47
00:02:35,582 --> 00:02:39,936
for each expert—representing the token's affinity for that specific specialist.

48
00:02:39,936 --> 00:02:42,750
To enforce sparsity, we apply a Top-K

49
00:02:42,750 --> 00:02:44,760
selection on the routing logits.

50
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:47,977
If we are using a Top-Two gating strategy,

51
00:02:47,977 --> 00:02:50,791
we identify the two experts with the

52
00:02:50,791 --> 00:02:53,606
highest raw routing scores, set the scores

53
00:02:53,606 --> 00:02:56,420
of all other experts to negative infinity,

54
00:02:56,420 --> 00:03:00,039
and apply the Softmax function over the remaining values.

55
00:03:00,039 --> 00:03:02,853
This produces a sparse gating vector where

56
00:03:02,853 --> 00:03:06,070
only the two chosen experts have non-zero probabilities,

57
00:03:06,070 --> 00:03:08,080
while the rest are zero.

58
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:10,894
This gating vector acts as a set

59
00:03:10,894 --> 00:03:13,709
of dynamic blending weights, determining how much

60
00:03:13,709 --> 00:03:17,328
influence each selected expert has on the final output.

61
00:03:17,328 --> 00:03:21,178
But training such a routing mechanism is notoriously unstable.

62
00:03:21,178 --> 00:03:23,318
Left to its own devices,

63
00:03:23,318 --> 00:03:26,313
a router is prone to a catastrophic

64
00:03:26,313 --> 00:03:28,880
failure mode known as routing collapse.

65
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:31,875
Early in training, a single expert might

66
00:03:31,875 --> 00:03:34,443
perform slightly better than the others.

67
00:03:34,443 --> 00:03:37,010
The router, seeking to minimize loss,

68
00:03:37,010 --> 00:03:40,005
begins sending more tokens to this expert.

69
00:03:40,005 --> 00:03:42,572
This expert gets more gradient updates,

70
00:03:42,572 --> 00:03:45,568
making it even better, which causes the

71
00:03:45,568 --> 00:03:48,135
router to send even more tokens.

72
00:03:48,135 --> 00:03:51,986
Soon, all tokens are routed to a single expert,

73
00:03:51,986 --> 00:03:54,981
reducing the model back to a small,

74
00:03:54,981 --> 00:03:59,688
under-capacity dense model while leaving other experts completely untrained and idle.

75
00:03:59,687 --> 00:04:02,805
To prevent routing collapse, researchers introduce an

76
00:04:02,805 --> 00:04:05,033
auxiliary load-balancing loss during training.

77
00:04:05,033 --> 00:04:09,932
This loss functions as a mathematical penalty for uneven token distribution.

78
00:04:09,932 --> 00:04:13,050
It is calculated by taking the dot

79
00:04:13,050 --> 00:04:16,168
product of two vectors: the fraction of

80
00:04:16,168 --> 00:04:20,177
tokens actually routed to each expert in a batch,

81
00:04:20,177 --> 00:04:23,295
and the average routing probability assigned to

82
00:04:23,295 --> 00:04:25,968
each expert across that same batch.

83
00:04:25,968 --> 00:04:28,195
By minimizing this load-balancing loss,

84
00:04:28,195 --> 00:04:31,758
we force the router to distribute tokens evenly,

85
00:04:31,758 --> 00:04:34,876
ensuring that all experts are utilized and

86
00:04:34,876 --> 00:04:37,103
trained to their full capacity.

87
00:04:37,103 --> 00:04:40,541
In hardware implementations, dynamic routing presents a

88
00:04:40,541 --> 00:04:44,961
massive engineering challenge: GPU parallelization requires static tensor shapes.

89
00:04:44,961 --> 00:04:49,381
If different experts receive vastly different numbers of tokens,

90
00:04:49,381 --> 00:04:52,819
we cannot execute them efficiently in parallel.

91
00:04:52,819 --> 00:04:56,257
To solve this, models define an Expert

92
00:04:56,257 --> 00:04:59,695
Capacity limit—the maximum number of tokens a

93
00:04:59,695 --> 00:05:03,624
single expert can process in a forward pass.

94
00:05:03,624 --> 00:05:08,044
If too few tokens are routed to an expert,

95
00:05:08,044 --> 00:05:11,482
its input tensor is padded with zeros.

96
00:05:11,482 --> 00:05:14,428
If too many tokens are sent,

97
00:05:14,428 --> 00:05:17,375
the excess tokens are dropped entirely,

98
00:05:17,375 --> 00:05:20,813
bypassing the expert via a residual connection.

99
00:05:20,813 --> 00:05:23,759
This maintains stable GPU execution times.

100
00:05:23,759 --> 00:05:27,607
The results of this engineering masterstroke are revolutionary.

101
00:05:27,607 --> 00:05:30,012
Take Mixtral eight-by-seven-billion, for example.

102
00:05:30,012 --> 00:05:32,897
It possesses forty-seven billion total parameters,

103
00:05:32,897 --> 00:05:36,745
but activates only thirteen billion parameters per token.

104
00:05:36,745 --> 00:05:40,111
This allows it to deliver the latency

105
00:05:40,111 --> 00:05:43,478
and speed of a thirteen-billion parameter model

106
00:05:43,478 --> 00:05:46,844
while matching or exceeding the accuracy and

107
00:05:46,844 --> 00:05:50,211
quality of a forty-seven-billion parameter dense giant.

108
00:05:50,211 --> 00:05:54,539
By separating total parameter capacity from active computational cost,

109
00:05:54,539 --> 00:05:57,906
Mixture of Experts pushes the boundaries of

110
00:05:57,906 --> 00:06:00,792
what is possible in modern AI.

111
00:06:00,791 --> 00:06:05,121
Mixture of Experts proves that intelligence doesn't require brute-force scale.

112
00:06:05,121 --> 00:06:08,152
By organizing parameters into specialized units and

113
00:06:08,152 --> 00:06:12,048
using a smart routing layer to dynamic dispatch work,

114
00:06:12,048 --> 00:06:15,079
we can build models that are both

115
00:06:15,079 --> 00:06:17,244
incredibly smart and computationally elegant.

116
00:06:17,244 --> 00:06:20,275
If you want to master the mathematical

117
00:06:20,275 --> 00:06:22,872
and hardware innovations of deep learning,

118
00:06:22,872 --> 00:06:27,635
hit the subscribe button for Gemini three point five Flash Model.

119
00:06:27,635 --> 00:06:30,233
Let's build the future of AI,

120
00:06:30,233 --> 00:06:33,263
one optimal routing decision at a time.
